{
  "texts": [
    "The rationale is that if, for example, the candidate article primarily pertains to a topic t 1 but also touches on a topic t 2 to a lesser extent, a journal that covers both of these topics appears more relevant than a journal covering only one of them.",
    "The top n journals foot_5 from this newly generated ranking are then recommended to the user, as depicted in Fig. 1.",
    "As we have seen, the recommendation process is based on information about topics (high level) as well as terms (low level) and their similarity to the query.",
    "However, the current system does not utilize any of the internal information it manages (such as what topics are discovered by the clustering algorithm, what articles and terms form the subprofiles associated with each journal, and what terms from these subprofiles match with those of the target article) to explain its recommendations.",
    "Instead, it simply provides an ordered list of recommended journals."
  ]
}